│ stop({"edit_points": [[4526, 4527, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp"]], │
│ "thoughts": "1. **Understanding the Issue**: The `vector-combine` pass crashes with a   │
│ segmentation fault when processing a specific LLVM IR. The crash occurs while iterating │
│ over instructions in a basic block. The backtrace points to an issue with iterator      │
│ invalidation, suggesting that an instruction is being used after it has been deleted,   │
│ or the instruction list is being corrupted.\n\n2. **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**: The `opt`  │
│ log shows that `vector-combine` performs a series of transformations:\n   - It          │
│ constant-folds an `and` instruction: `%and = and <4 x i32> %inselt, zeroinitializer` is │
│ replaced.\n   - It then proceeds to erase several instructions that it considers dead   │
│ code: `%and`, `%inselt`, `%phi`, and `%reduce`.\n   - The erasure of the `%phi` node is │
│ suspicious because it has a use by itself (a loop-carried dependency through            │
│ `%reduce`). Erasing it breaks the data flow of the loop.\n   - The final line of the    │
│ log, `VC: Visiting: <badref> = call <cannot get addrspace!> i32 <null operand!>(`,      │
│ confirms that the IR has been corrupted. The pass is trying to visit an instruction     │
│ that has been deleted.\n\n3. **Root Cause Analysis**:\n   - The core of the problem     │
│ lies in the `VectorCombine::run()` function, which iterates over instructions in a      │
│ basic block using `llvm::make_early_inc_range(BB)`. This creates an                     │
│ `early_inc_iterator` that is supposed to be safe against instruction deletion.\n   -    │
│ The pass identifies that the `and` instruction can be folded. After this, it uses       │
│ `RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions` to clean up now-unused instructions.\n   - │
│ The issue is that `RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions` deletes the `%phi` node. │
│ The `%phi` node has a use from the `%reduce` instruction within the same loop. However, │
│ the pass incorrectly determines the `%phi` is dead.\n   - When `%phi` is deleted, its   │
│ operand `%reduce` is also considered dead and deleted.\n   - The `early_inc_iterator`   │
│ in `VectorCombine::run()` was pointing to one of the instructions in the block (e.g.,   │
│ `%phi`). When `RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions` erases a chain of            │
│ instructions including the one the iterator was pre-incremented to point to, the        │
│ iterator becomes invalid.\n   - In the next iteration of the loop in                    │
│ `VectorCombine::run()`, dereferencing this invalid iterator leads to a segmentation     │
│ fault. The `opt` log's `<badref>` line shows the pass attempting to access a deleted    │
│ instruction.\n   - The fundamental flaw is that                                         │
│ `RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions` is too aggressive in this context. It does │
│ not correctly handle the loop-carried dependency of the PHI node, leading it to delete  │
│ live instructions and corrupt the IR, which in turn invalidates the iterator being used │
│ by its caller.\n\n4. **Proposed Edit Point(s)**:\n   The fix is to remove the call to   │
│ `RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions` from the main instruction processing loop  │
│ in `VectorCombine::run()`. Dead code elimination should be handled by a separate,       │
│ dedicated pass (like `instcombine` or `ADCE`) that runs after `vector-combine` and has  │
│ a more global and correct view of instruction liveness. This prevents `vector-combine`  │
│ from incorrectly deleting instructions and corrupting its own iteration.\n\n   -        │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp`\n   - **Edit Point**:\n     │
│ ```cpp\n     // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp:4522\n     if (NewInst) │
│ {\n       ++NumVecComb;\n       if (NewInst != &I)\n                                    │
│ I.replaceAllUsesWith(NewInst);\n       if (!I.isTerminator())\n                         │
│ RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions(&I, &TLI);\n     }\n     ```\n     **to**\n  │
│ ```cpp\n     // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp:4522\n     if (NewInst) │
│ {\n       ++NumVecComb;\n       if (NewInst != &I)\n                                    │
│ I.replaceAllUsesWith(NewInst);\n       // We can't recursively delete dead instructions │
│ here because it can\n       // invalidate our iterators.\n       // if                  │
│ (!I.isTerminator())\n       //  RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions(&I, &TLI);\n │
│ }\n     ```\n   I will comment out the `if` block containing the problematic            │
│ call.\n\n5. **Conclusion**: The segmentation fault is caused by `vector-combine`        │
│ over-aggressively deleting what it perceives as dead instructions within its main       │
│ processing loop. The function `RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions` does not     │
│ correctly account for all use-def chains, particularly loop-carried dependencies,       │
│ leading to the deletion of live instructions. This corrupts the basic block's           │
│ instruction list and invalidates the iterator used in `VectorCombine::run()`, causing a │
│ crash. By removing this unsafe recursive deletion, we ensure the pass only performs its │
│ primary vector combination transformations and leaves the cleanup of dead code to other │
│ passes that are designed to do it safely. This resolves the crash and makes the pass    │
│ more robust."})                                                                         │
